198":"1142–1198","1042–1118":"1042–1118","1060–1120":"1060–1120","1080":"1080","1198":"1198","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1042":"1042","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1060":"1060","Abt 1118":"circa 1118","1118":"1118","1106":"1106","1135":"1135","1146":"1146","Abt 1100":"circa 1100","1100":"1100","Abt 1080":"circa 1080","1207":"1207","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hawksworth, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hawksworth, Nottinghamshire, England","Hornby Castle, Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Walcot, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Walcot, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1100–1135":"about 1100–1135","1080–1146":"1080–1146","1100–1135":"1100–1135","1110–1162":"1110–1162","1140–1207":"1140–1207","1142–1198":"1142–1198","1042–1118":"1042–1118","1060–1120":"1060–1120","1080":"1080","1198":"1198","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1042":"1042","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1060":"1060","Abt 1118":"about 1118","1118":"1118","1106":"1106","1135":"1135","1146":"1146","Abt 1100":"about 1100","1100":"1100","Abt 1080":"about 1080","1207":"1207","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Hawksworth, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hawksworth, Nottinghamshire, England","Hornby Castle, Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Walcot, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Walcot, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Néville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Jollan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanized or Americanized form of Polish, Czech, and Sorbian   Polan  .","English: unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Polan","meanings":["Transferred use of the Irish surname, Gaelic <i>Ó Nualláin</i> ‘descendant of <i>Nuallán</i>’. The latter is an ancient Gaelic personal name, originally a byname representing a diminutive of <i>nuall</i> ‘chariot-fighter, champion’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jollan de Néville I was born about 1100, in Hawksworth, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Gilbert de Neville, was 60 and his mother, Philicia de Damoys, was 41. He married Mary FitzRichard in 1135, in Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1135, in Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, Unit